{"title_page": "Lake Hamilton and Lake Catherine", "text_new": "{{Tone|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Lake Hamilton and Lake Catherine''' are a pair of [[man-made lake]]s around [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]]. The two lakes have greatly improved the tourism in Hot Springs. Both Lakes were created by Arkansas Power & Light (now a subsidiary of [[Entergy]]).\n\n{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Lake Hamilton\n | image = Lake_Hamilton_AR-kmf.JPG\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Garland County, Arkansas|Garland County]], [[Arkansas]],<br>[[United States]]\n | coords = {{coord|34.4325|-93.0887|type:waterbody_region:US-AR|display=inline}}\n | type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = [[Ouachita River]]\n | outflow = [[Ouachita River]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = {{convert|7200|acre|ha|abbr=on}}\n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n\n==Lake Hamilton==\n'''Lake Hamilton''' is a {{convert|7200|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[reservoir]] near [[Lake Hamilton, Arkansas]] and Hot Springs, Arkansas. It is located on the [[Ouachita River]], one of Arkansas's most popular rivers. It is formed from '''Carpenter Dam''' which was named after [[Flavius Josephus Carpenter]].  The dam is over {{convert|1000|ft|m}} long and {{convert|100|ft|m}} high, and has a [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric power generation facility]] and completed in 1931.  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1992.<ref name=Carpenter>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkansaspreservation.com/National-Register-Listings/PDF/GA0078.nr.pdf|title=NRHP nomination for Carpenter Dam|publisher=Arkansas Preservation|accessdate=2015-05-14}}</ref>\n\nAlong with Lake Catherine and [[Lake Ouachita]], Lake Hamilton is one of the lakes that helps make Hot Springs a boon for tourism. The lake was created in 1932, mainly to generate hydroelectricity, but now it also serves as a recreational getaway. Much of the lake is surrounded with resorts, restaurants, and motels. Parasailing, boating, fishing, and waterskiing are popular on Lake Hamilton, and the rest of the lakes around Hot Springs. A 400-passenger riverboat called the Belle of Hot Springs offers cruises on Lake Hamilton. [[Garvan Woodland Gardens]], a {{convert|210|acre|ha|adj=on}} botanical park is also accessible by boat.\n\nLake Hamilton was named after Hamilton Moses who later became President and Chairman of the Board for Arkansas Power and Light.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entergy.com/operations_information/hydro/utility_powerremmel.aspx |title=Remmel, Catherine, Carpenter, and Hamilton: Who were they? }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=2356 |title=Colter Hamilton (Ham) Moses (1888\u20131966) }}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 1999, an accident involving the tourist boats on Lake Hamilton resulted in the deaths of thirteen persons. Former [[Arkansas State Senate|State Senator]] [[Jim Keet]], the 2010 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[gubernatorial]] [[nominee]], was boating with his family at the time of the tragedy. Four years earlier, Senator Keet had co-sponsored a bill that added several new water safety rules to the Arkansas code, including the requirement that children wear life preservers on most boats. However, the provision did not apply to [[DUKW]] (\"duck\") boats, the kind involved in the tragedy, which sank with barely thirty seconds of warning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbbi.com/folders/acc/arktour/arktour.htm\n|title=\"12 dead in tourist boat accident at Hot Springs,\" May 2, 1999|publisher=Northwest Arkansas Times: rrbi.com|accessdate=May 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nLake Hamilton.jpg|Lake Hamilton viewed from Garvan Woodland Gardens property.\nLake Hamilton 004.jpg|Lake Hamilton \nLake Hamilton 002.jpg|Lake Hamilton \nGarvan Woodland Gardens 001.jpg|Garvan Woodlands Gardens by Lake Hamilton\nGarvan Woodland Gardens 002.jpg|Garvan Woodlands Gardens by Lake Hamilton\n</gallery>\n\n==Lake Catherine==\n{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Lake Catherine\n | image = Lake Catherine AR-kmf.JPG\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Garland County, Arkansas|Garland]] / [[Hot Spring County, Arkansas|Hot Spring]] counties, [[Arkansas]], [[United States]]\n | coords = {{coord|34.4442|-92.9134|type:waterbody_region:US-AR|display=inline}}\n | type = \n | inflow = \n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = {{convert|1940|acre|ha|abbr=on}}\n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Catherine''' is a small {{convert|1940|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[lake]] near Hot Springs.  '''Lake Catherine State Park''' is located on the lake's shore. The state park contains 18 cabins. Lake Catherine Boom boom was created in the 1920s with the building of '''Remmel Dam''', a concrete-and-steel Ambursen-type buttressed dam. Remmel Dam was created to provide hydroelectricity, but recreation came as a result of lake's location next to Hot Springs.  Remmel Dam is also listed on the National Register of Historic Places.\n\n<gallery>\nNPS hot-springs-regional-map.pdf|Regional map over Hot Springs\nLake Catherine State Park 001.jpg|Lake Catherine  \n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Arkansas dams and reservoirs]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Garland County, Arkansas]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060516142456/http://www.arkansasstateparks.com/parks/park.asp?id=2 Lake Catherine State Park]\n*[http://www.arkansas.com/lakes-rivers/lake/id/11 Lake Catherine]\n*[http://www.arkansas.com/lakes-rivers/lake/id/18 Lake Hamilton]\n\n{{Protected areas of Arkansas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lake Hamilton And Lake Catherine}}\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Arkansas|Hamilton]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Garland County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Garland County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Garland County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Dams on the National Register of Historic Places in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Garland County, Arkansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Lake Hamilton and Lake Catherine''' are a pair of [[man-made lake]]s around [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]]. The two lakes have greatly improved the tourism in Hot Springs. Both Lakes were created by Arkansas Power & Light (now a subsidiary of [[Entergy]]).\n\n{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Lake Hamilton\n | image = Lake_Hamilton_AR-kmf.JPG\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Garland County, Arkansas|Garland County]], [[Arkansas]],<br>[[United States]]\n | coords = {{coord|34.4325|-93.0887|type:waterbody_region:US-AR|display=inline}}\n | type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = [[Ouachita River]]\n | outflow = [[Ouachita River]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = {{convert|7200|acre|ha|abbr=on}}\n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n\n==Lake Hamilton==\n'''Lake Hamilton''' is a {{convert|7200|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[reservoir]] near [[Lake Hamilton, Arkansas]] and Hot Springs, Arkansas. It is located on the [[Ouachita River]], one of Arkansas's most popular rivers. It is formed 